{"componentChunkName":"component---src-pages-posts-js","path":"/posts/","result":{"data":{"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"20b091f3-b324-557e-bf9b-d33dc5dce1e5","html":"<p>The react and node based <a href=\"http://www.gatsbyjs.com\">Gatsby</a> takes a lot of the pain and configuration away from utilizing react and react-router to create and generate multi-page 'static' websites. (In fact, the newest version of Gatsby makes use of reach-router- a router that borrows from several react-router style components)</p>\n<p>Because Gatsby is based on React components, sites could even generate some content dynamically, say, by using an external API.</p>\n<p>The real appeal to me, currently, is the abilty to parse markdown files into self-contained pages 'semi-dynamically'(at build time). This is great for something like this website, as I expect content updates to be relatively infrequent, but appreciate the scalability and easy of use of simply, putting a markdown file in the correct location and running <code>gatsby build</code>.</p>\n<p><figure class='gatsby-resp-image-figure' style=''>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-wrapper' style='position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 559px; '>\n      <a class='gatsby-resp-image-link' href='/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/a65ce/frontmatter.png' style='display: block' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-background-image' style=\"padding-bottom: 16%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAADCAIAAAAcOLh5AAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAfElEQVQI1y2Oaw6DQAiEPUg1vAbch8lq+7f3v1ZZK4EEhskHi0ZjRIU0WIHtps1R3dZ1fd35xPbUVLbtry9+fb2PcZ3vzzmOUkwTUWEm7Cahko0JKZMKQwQqQuTKwrSgHIydopNYWsu8r7kL0x7oPn+5lQlqgeQmpUJz/AHxLxlYspPcAAAAAABJRU5ErkJggg=='); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class='gatsby-resp-image-image' alt='*markdown frontmatter is programatically read to create this post*' title='*markdown frontmatter is programatically read to create this post*' src='/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/a65ce/frontmatter.png' srcset='/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/8a4e8/frontmatter.png 150w,\n/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/5a46d/frontmatter.png 300w,\n/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/a65ce/frontmatter.png 559w' sizes='(max-width: 559px) 100vw, 559px' style='width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;' loading='lazy'>\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class='gatsby-resp-image-figcaption'><p><em>markdown frontmatter is programatically read to create this post</em></p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>There have been plenty of resources to aid in configuring this setup, though I will say working with Gatsby's data api is daunting.</p>\n<p><figure class='gatsby-resp-image-figure' style=''>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-wrapper' style='position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 595px; '>\n      <a class='gatsby-resp-image-link' href='/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/3dd3e/createnode.png' style='display: block' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-background-image' style=\"padding-bottom: 36.66666666666667%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class='gatsby-resp-image-image' alt='*setting up programatic page generation isnt intuitive, but is logical*' title='*setting up programatic page generation isnt intuitive, but is logical*' src='/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/3dd3e/createnode.png' srcset='/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/8a4e8/createnode.png 150w,\n/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/5a46d/createnode.png 300w,\n/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/3dd3e/createnode.png 595w' sizes='(max-width: 595px) 100vw, 595px' style='width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;' loading='lazy'>\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class='gatsby-resp-image-figcaption'><p><em>setting up programatic page generation isnt intuitive, but is logical</em></p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>I found the <a href=\"https://gatsbyjs.com/tutorial/part-four\">data in gatsby</a> tutorial particularly helpful.</p>\n<p><figure class='gatsby-resp-image-figure' style=''>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-wrapper' style='position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 489px; '>\n      <a class='gatsby-resp-image-link' href='/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/03e1f/graphql.png' style='display: block' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-background-image' style=\"padding-bottom: 62.66666666666667%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class='gatsby-resp-image-image' alt='*gatsby utilizes Graphql queries*' title='*gatsby utilizes Graphql queries*' src='/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/03e1f/graphql.png' srcset='/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/8a4e8/graphql.png 150w,\n/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/5a46d/graphql.png 300w,\n/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/03e1f/graphql.png 489w' sizes='(max-width: 489px) 100vw, 489px' style='width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;' loading='lazy'>\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class='gatsby-resp-image-figcaption'><p><em>gatsby utilizes Graphql queries</em></p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Gatsby works with its own GraphQL system, something with which I have very little familiarity- though the query language looks extremely flexible. I'm looking forward to learning more about GraphQL, maybe through the <a href=\"https://fullstackopen.com/en/\">Full Stack Open</a> course- which I have been curious about exploring for a while.</p>\n<p>Building this website has (so far) felt fairly intuitive- I'm really looking forward to learning more about gatsby, and adding it to my tool-belt.</p>","fields":{"slug":"/posts/10.30.20/Working_with_gatsby/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Working with Gatsby","date":"10/30/20","description":"Learning to use a new framework built on the power of react.","image":{"publicURL":"/tknapp/static/b35bb12e5b3c28c136e7daccb9c0dea3/Gatsby-Monogram.svg","relativePath":"10.30.20/images/Gatsby-Monogram.svg","name":"Gatsby-Monogram"}}}},{"node":{"id":"dc03e28a-a926-5184-888c-5f969ff1af88","html":"<p>It might be my inner New Englander, but I <em>love</em> a difficult thing. I've been learning\nto use <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vim_(text_editor)\">Vim</a> for the last 4 months. <del>I'm\nnot sure its actually made me any faster at writing code.</del> It has NOT made me any\nfaster at writing code, but it has changed the way I think about editing code. I still\nmostly work in Vscode, but use the <a href=\"https://github.com/VSCodeVim/Vim\">VscodeVim</a> extension.</p>\n<p>Here are the two things I learned today, while working on a lyrics guessing game\ninspired by the brothers over at <a href=\"https://www.themcelroy.family/mbmbam\">MBMBAM</a>.</p>\n<h2>Incrementing Numbers</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p><kbd>cntrl + a</kbd> Increments.\n<kbd>cntrl + x</kbd> Decrements.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><img src=\"/tknapp/static/inc-f765c94a95a7451cee9fbcf514210228.gif\" alt=\"incrementing the number under the cursor with vim\"></p>\n<p>While creating some dummy JSON files to use in development, I wanted to append number\ntags to a lyrics field to id tracks in the 'lyrics display'. After copying and pasting\nblocks of JSON information, I didn't really want to append the numbers to each line.</p>\n<p>But I didn't have to increment each number each time! In comes <strong>Visual Block</strong> to\nthe rescue!</p>\n<p><figure class='gatsby-resp-image-figure' style=''>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-wrapper' style='position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 144px; '>\n      <a class='gatsby-resp-image-link' href='/tknapp/static/ca343873177760394f3eb23c56095f7c/75706/visualblock.png' style='display: block' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-background-image' style=\"padding-bottom: 17.36111111111111%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class='gatsby-resp-image-image' alt='&lt;kbd&gt;cntrl + v&lt;/kbd&gt; Enters visual block mode' title='&lt;kbd&gt;cntrl + v&lt;/kbd&gt; Enters visual block mode' src='/tknapp/static/ca343873177760394f3eb23c56095f7c/75706/visualblock.png' srcset='/tknapp/static/ca343873177760394f3eb23c56095f7c/75706/visualblock.png 144w' sizes='(max-width: 144px) 100vw, 144px' style='width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;' loading='lazy'>\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class='gatsby-resp-image-figcaption'><p><kbd>cntrl + v</kbd> Enters visual block mode</p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Then, after selecting all my numbers down the column, the command <kbd>g</kbd> +\n<kbd>cntrl + a</kbd> will increment the numbers, creating a sequence. (note: using just\n<kbd>cntrl + a</kbd> would increment all the numbers but not in sequence.)</p>\n<p><img src=\"/tknapp/static/colinc-2605081c330be9e2dfc60ebc1618c0e5.gif\" alt=\"Incrementing a whole column of numbers, sequentially!\"></p>\n<h2>Cursor Placement after search.</h2>\n<p>Something I also found necessary was repeating an action on search results, but at a\nspecific location within the word. For example changing multiple variables from\n<code>setSign</code> to <code>setNumberSign</code>.</p>\n<p>While <kbd>c</kbd><kbd>a</kbd><kbd>w</kbd> + <code>setNumberSign</code> in combination with <kbd>.</kbd> would probably be the fastest way here. But for the sake of argument (because I can't think of a different use pattern at the moment.) I'll demonstrate an alternative.</p>\n<p>After entering search mode, I enter the query (<code>/setSign</code>) to find all instances of\n<code>setSign</code>. Then by appending <code>/b+3</code> to my search, the cursor will land on the <code>S</code>.\nEntering <code>/e</code> after a search will place the cursor at the end of the result.</p>\n<p>Furthermore <code>/e+3</code> would place the cursor 3 spaces after the end.</p>\n<p>So an alternative to using <kbd>c</kbd><kbd>a</kbd><kbd>w</kbd>,\n<kbd>n</kbd>,<kbd>.</kbd> <em>could</em> be:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><code>/setSign/b+3</code>,<kbd>i<kbd><code>Number</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>followed by using <kbd>n</kbd> to get the next search result, and <kbd>.</kbd> to\n<kbd>.</kbd> repeat the insertion.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/tknapp/static/searchcursor-39fb1ebb70250869342f068502b265b8.gif\" alt=\"&#x60;/setSign/b+3&#x60; in action\"></p>\n<p>Pretty cool.</p>\n<p>Well, now that I've spent all this time writing this post, I can assuredly say, that\nVim has made me significantly slower at getting work done. Oh well.</p>","fields":{"slug":"/posts/11.2.20/2_New_Things_I_Learned_in_Vim/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"2 New things I learned in vim.","date":"11/02/20","description":"Number incrementing and cursor placement in search results.","image":{"publicURL":"/tknapp/static/edd82a56983cf47ddb29615fc043735e/ibmKeys.jpg","relativePath":"11.2.20/images/ibmKeys.jpg","name":"ibmKeys"}}}}]}},"pageContext":{}},"staticQueryHashes":[]}